he same commodity.\n- **Fix**: Replace the recursive call with direct in-place arithmetic. Resolve the target entry once, operate on it directly, then erase if realzero. Do not recurse.\n\n```cpp\n// In the else branch:\nif (!amt.commodity().has_annotation() && amt.sign() < 0) {\n  const string& base_symbol = amt.commodity().base_symbol();\n  for (auto it = amounts.begin(); it != amounts.end(); ++it) {\n    if (it->first->has_annotation() && it->first->base_symbol() == base_symbol) {\n      it->second -= amt.negated();  // subtract abs(sale) from lot\n      if (it->second.is_realzero())\n        amounts.erase(it);\n      return *this;\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### [CRITICAL] `const_cast` of pool-owned commodity pointer in `match_lot` is unsafe\n\n- **File**: `/Users/johnw/src/ledger/fix-164/src/pool.cc#L430-L435`\n- **Category**: Bug / Memory Safety\n- **Confidence**: 90\n- **Problem**: `matched_comm` is retrieved as `const annotated_commodity_t*` from the pool's `annotated_commodities` map (which stores `shared_ptr<annotated_commodity_t>`). The code then calls `matched_amount.set_commodity(const_cast<annotated_commodity_t&>(*matched_comm))`. `set_commodity` stores a raw `commodity_t*` pointer directly into `amount_t::commodity_`. While the pool keeps the `shared_ptr` alive, the `const_cast` itself is benign in isolation — but it is unnecessary and misleading, and it opens the door for callers who modify the commodity through the returned amount to corrupt the pool's shared object. The standard pattern in this codebase (see `amount.h:571`, `history.cc:317`) is to `const_cast` only when the commodity is known to be mutable; here it is a pool-managed object whose `details` field should remain immutable after creation.\n- **Impact**: Accidental mutation of a shared pool commodity through the returned amount's non-const commodity reference will corrupt every amount that uses the same lot.\n- **Fix**: Retrieve a non-const pointer from the pool directly via `pair.seco